From 422c68c86b7f6d132ed4494067bed78181c4ba41 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Hexkalibur <ordo-imperialis@protonmail.com>
Date: Sat, 4 Jul 2026 18:39:01 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] v0.2: evidence-based memory triage, shared helpers, noise
 reduction

The v0.1 memory scanner alerted HIGH on every process holding a single
private RWX region, which on a normal desktop is almost entirely false
positives (JIT engines, browsers, .NET/CLR hosts, Defender's own AMSI
process, one alert per backgroundTaskHost.exe instance -- 79 of the 82
alerts in the last scan were this). v0.2 keeps the same region walk but
adds real evidence before raising severity:

- Mapped-PE detection: private executable regions are read back and
  checked for an MZ/PE header. A manually mapped module in private
  memory is a near-certain reflective-injection footprint
  (ALERT_INJECTED_PE, CRITICAL).
- Thread-start correlation: every thread's Win32 start address is
  resolved (NtQueryInformationThread) and checked against private
  executable regions -- the signature of CreateRemoteThread/APC
  shellcode (ALERT_INJECTED_THREAD, CRITICAL).
- A built-in + configurable (allow_rwx) JIT allow-list so plain RWX
  with no PE/thread evidence in known hosts becomes evidence, not an
  alert. memory_strict restores the raw v0.1 behavior.

Other additions:
- src/util.c centralizes staging-path checks, Authenticode/catalog
  verification, and IP-block matching that were previously copy-pasted
  across process.c, network.c, persistence.c and kernel.c.
- A suspicious command-line / script pattern table (encoded PowerShell,
  LOLBin proxy execution, ransomware/anti-forensic indicators), used by
  both the live process scanner (via PEB command-line reads) and 4688
  event records.
- CIDR-range IP blocking, an expanded known-ports list so routine
  Windows services (NTP/NetBIOS/DHCP/SSDP/LLMNR/mDNS/WS-Discovery/IKE)
  stop being flagged as UNKNOWN_SERVICE, a same-scan multi-endpoint
  beacon heuristic for staging-path processes, Defender-operational-log
  correlation, and operator-defined alert suppression.
